{
  "texts": [
    "Applying Theorem 2.6, the idempotents in the rational Goodwillie-Burnside ring 𝐴 Q (3) are given by𝑒 3 = 1 6 • [3], 𝑒 2 = 1 2 • [2] -1 2 • [3], 𝑒 1 = [1] -1 2 • [2] + 1 3 • [3].Our final low dimensional example highlights the passage between the Goodwillie-Burnside ring 𝐴(𝑑 -1) and the Goodwillie Burnside ring 𝐴(𝑑) through the inclusion of Epi ≤𝑑-1 as a full subcategory of Epi ≤𝑑, which satisfies the conditions of Theorem 2.8.Example 3.4.",
    "The category Epi ≤4 may be displayed pictorially as[4] [1] [2][3]24 14 2 6 6 36In this case we have that the hom-set matrix and its inverse are given by 𝐻 = 1 0 0 0 1 2 0 0 1 6 6 0 1 14 36 24, 𝐻 -1 = 1 0 0 0 -1 2 1 2 0 0 1 3 -1 2 1 6 0 -1 4 11 24 -1 4 1 24.The rational idempotents of 𝐴 Q (4) are given by𝑒 4 = 1 24 • [4], 𝑒 3 = 1 6 • [3] -1 4 • [4], 𝑒 2 = 1 2 • [2] -1 2 • [3] + 11 24 • [4], 𝑒 1 = [1] -1 2 • [2] + 1 3 • [3] -1 4 • [4].The inclusion of the full subcategory Epi ≤3 ↩→ Epi ≤4 induces a ring map 𝐴 Q (4) → 𝐴 Q (3).",
    "This inclusion of the full subcategory satisfies the conditions of Theorem 2.8, so the kernel is generated by [4] ∈ 𝐴 Q (4).",
    "By our computation of the idempotents above, this is equivalent to the kernel being generated by the \"top idempotent\" 𝑒 4.We now summarise the previous examples in the general case of the category of finite sets of cardinality at most 𝑑 and epimorphisms.Example 3.5.",
    "The hom-set matrix for Epi ≤𝑑 and its inverse are given by𝐻 = 1 0 0 • • • 0 1 2 0 • • • 0 1 6 3!"
